    body: "A first date in your 60s, 70s, or 80s is a small adventure. You may have been on hundreds of first dates in your younger years, or you may be returning to dating after 40 years of marriage. Either way, the rules have changed a little. The good news is that the basics still hold: pick a public place, keep it short, dress like yourself, and pay attention to how you feel. The new parts are mostly about safety, technology, and a bit more honesty than dating in your 20s required.\n\nThe single biggest mistake new senior daters make is planning a date that is too long. A four-hour dinner with a stranger feels heavy even when the conversation flows well. If the chemistry is not there, four hours feels like four days. A 60 to 90 minute coffee or lunch in a busy public place is plenty for a first meeting. If both of you want to spend more time together, you can extend on the spot. If one of you does not, you can wrap up at the planned time without anyone feeling trapped.\n\nThe second mistake is overdressing or underdressing. The right outfit is one that feels like you on a good day, not a costume. If you would never wear a tie, do not wear one to a coffee shop on a Tuesday afternoon. If you love a particular scarf or a favorite pair of earrings, wear those. Comfortable shoes matter more than fashion at this stage of life. If you cannot walk to and from the car without pain, the rest of the date will not go well.\n\nThis guide walks through choosing the date location, picking the time and day, getting ready, the safety steps to take before you go, what to talk about and what to skip, how to handle the bill, and how to end the date in a way that leaves room for a second one if you want it. We also cover the gentle ways to say no thank you if the match was not what you hoped.",
